@node "Limitations" "Limitations of the unregistered version"
 A keyfile is required for MultiPack to work fully. Without a keyfile MultiPack has several limitations:

 o it will only let users launch MultiPack 20 times.

 o it will pack a maximum of approximately 100 messages per session
   (this is approximate because MultiPack will not start packing
   an area it cannot finish).

 o it let's you know in a few places that it's unregistered
   (including on the tearline of imported messages).

To obtain a registered version of MultiPack, see the @{" registration " link "registration" 0} section of this document.
@endnode

@node "require" "System requirements"
 MultiPack requires that you are running DLG Professional and v2.04 or later of the Amiga operating system.
@endnode

@node "install" "Installation of MultiPack"

 o Assign DOORS: somewhere, if you haven't already.

 o Execute Install.bat. This will do the following:

        o Copy the included MultiPack.menun to DLGConfig:Menu.

        o Copy the .library files to libs:

        o Create the directory DOORS:MultiPack, and copy the
          MultiPack executable, and the '.fmt' files there.

 o Add a menu entry to some menu on your system to call
   MultiPack as a submenu.

 o Re-configure the 'M' (Main menu) command in the MultiPack
   menu to return to the menu you called the MultiPack menu from.

 o You may want to create a subdirectory directory called
   "Work" in your new MultiPack directory for MultiPack
   to use for temporary storage (although it can be
   elsewhere).

 o Configure MultiPack (Option 'S') on the provided menu
   (see the "Configuring MultiPack" section).

 o Configure each packer library. Do this by selecting the
   packer (using the 'C' menu entry) and then choosing the
   'L' menu entry.

 o That's it!
@endnode

@node "Config" "Configuring MultiPack"
 There are four levels at which MultiPack has to be configured:

 o @{" General " link "genconfig" 0} options for the main program must be
   configured by the Sysop.

 o @{" User-specific " link "userconfig" 0} options for the main program must
   be configured by each user.

 o General options for each packer library (@{" ASCII " link "ASCII" 0}, @{" QWK " link "QWK" 0},
   and @{" BlueWave " link "BWAVE" 0}) must be configured by the Sysop.

 o User-specific options for each packer library (@{" ASCII " link "ASCII" 0}, @{" QWK " link "QWK" 0},
   and @{" BlueWave " link "BWAVE" 0}) must be configured by each user.
@endnode

@node "genconfig" "General MultiPack configuration"
 The general MultiPack options (Option 'S' on the menu) are:

 o Work path -- this should be the path to a directory
   for MultiPack to use as temporary storage. It will
   be "DOORS:MultiPack/Work" if you did as I suggested
   earlier.

 o Ram thresh -- this is the default ram threshold.

 o Bkgrnd thresh -- this is the default background threshold.

 o Baud max factor -- specifies a maximum number of messages to pack
                      based on the user's baud rate. The formula used
                      to calculate the maximum is:

                      max=<baud>/100*<baud max factor>

                      So, if this value was set to 1, and the user was at
                      2400 baud, they could pack a maximum of 24 messages.
                      A valude of 0 means no limit will be imposed.

 o Task priority -- the task priority MultiPack will run at.

 o Options

   (Q) Bkgrnd quiet -- whether to suppress output when in background mode.
                       MultiPack runs itself in the background by launching
                       a TPTCron event. If you use a window to view TPTCron's
                       output, and you don't want to see MultiPack's output
                       there, you will want to use this option.
@endnode

@node "userconfig" "User-specific MultiPack configuration"
 The user-specific MultiPack options are:

 o Name -- user's name (not editable).

 o Archiver -- the archiver used to pack mail.

 o Packer -- the packer library to be used.

 o Max # messages -- the (approximate) maximum number of messages
                     MultiPack will pack for you. A value of 0 means
                     no limit will be imposed.

 o Options -- several boolean options:

   (P) Pack pvt msgs? -- whether to pack a user's private
                         mail directory.

   (F) Pack foregrnd? -- whether to always pack in the foreground
                         regardless of the number of messages.

   (D) Delete packets? -- whether to delete mail packets after
                          they have been unpacked.

   (E) Pack empty? -- whether to pack empty message areas (useful
                      if you want to have them listed in an off-line
                      reader).

 o Launches -- the number of times the user has launched MultiPack
               (not editable).
@endnode

@node "ASCII" "ASCII Format"
 The library mpfascii.library packs messages much like DLG's MailPack program. There are no sysop configuration options for this library. There is one value for the user to configure:

  o Wrap width -- The screen width to use when word-wrapping messages.
@endnode

@node "qwk" "QWK Format"
 The library mpfqwk.library packs and unpacks messages in QWK format. The following options must be configured by the sysop:

  o PacketID -- An eight character ID for your system, generally
                your BBS name.

  o Location -- Where you live (City, State).

  o BBSPhone # -- Your BBS phone number.

  o Hello file -- Path to a 'Greeting' text file to be included in the
                  archive. This file should use IBM (CR/LF) line termination.
                  Use the included @{" TxtConvert " link "txtconvert" 0} program.

  o Goodbye file -- Path to a 'Goodbye' text file to be included in the
                    archive. This file should use IBM (CR/LF) line
                    termination. Use the included @{" TxtConvert " link "txtconvert" 0} program.

The following options are available to the user:

  o Packet name ext -- A three-character extention that the BlueWave
                       packer will use to create the name of the
                       message archive. A '#' placed somewhere in the
                       extension will be replaced by a number from
                       0-9 to allow for multiple packets to pile up
                       in your user directory.
@endnode

@node "BWave" "BlueWave Format"
 The library mpfbw.library packs and unpacks messages in BlueWave format. The following options must be configured by the sysop:

  o PacketID -- An eight character ID for your system, generally
                your BBS name.

The following options are available to the user:

  o Packet name ext -- A three-character extention that the BlueWave
                       packer will use to create the name of the
                       message archive. A '#' placed somewhere in the
                       extension will be replaced by a number from
                       0-9 to allow for multiple packets to pile up
                       in the user's directory.
@endnode

@node "txtconvert" "TxtConvert utility"
 This utility converts text files from Amiga line termination format to MSDos format. To run it, type:

 TxtConvert <infile >outfile

@endnode

@node "arch" "Notes about archivers"
 MultiPack uses DLG's archiver settings to pack/extract messages. Because the amiga version of Zip (AmyZip) supports neither "*" or "#?" wildcards, the source directory used when translating the DLG archiver strings is the directory containing the files t

 o pack. For example, if the files to pack were in:

  DOORS:MultiPack/Work/Mike_Oliphant.mptmp

and the archiver pack string was:

  Zip -r -j ~d ~s

then the translated string would look something like:

  Zip -r -j USER:Mike_Oliphant/MYBBS.MO0 DOORS:MultiPack/Work/Mike_Oliphant.mptmp

Note that in your Zip configuration, you must have the "-r -j" options in your archive string. This tells Zip to recursively pack directories, but not keep track of the filenames.

Note that this method of packing will prevent some archivers from being used, but it seems unlikely that anything other than LHA or Zip compression will be needed.

@endnode

@node "using" "How to use MultiPack"
 Using MultiPack is fairly intuitive. After the MultiPack program and packer libraries have been configured by the Sysop and by the user, the user simply selects the Pack or Unpack menu options.

Packing:

  o All areas in a user's selected archive area list will be packed.

  o Packing takes place either in the foreground (while the user waits),
    or in the background (while the user does other things). Which method is
    used depends on the number of messages to be packed, and how the Sysop
    and user have configured MultiPack. If packing occurs in the background,
    the user is notified when it is finished.

  o If the user is packing in foreground mode, they will be given the option
    to download the mail packet directly from MultiPack. Otherwise, the
    mail packet will be placed in their private directory for download.


UnPacking:

  o Archives to unpack are either uploaded directly to MultiPack by the user,
    or are taken from a user's private directory (which is scanned for
    appropriate files).

  o If the packet is to be found the user's private directory, it must have
    the style of filename expected by the packer (for example, MYBBS.REP
    for a QWK reply file uploaded to the system "MYBBS").

  o The packet(s) found will be unarchived, and the messages will be placed
    on the system.
@endnode

@node "calling" "How to call MultiPack from a DLG menu"
 Here are the arguments you use to call MultiPack:

 MultiPack [-U <user_name> -R <ramthresh> -T <bkgthresh>]
           [-B -C -S -E -O <pri> -F <file> -L <library>]

 Where:

  -U <user_name> is the underscored user name to pack for
              (need only be specified in background mode
  -R <ramthresh> is the # of msgs to be packed in ram
  -T <bkgthresh> is the # of msgs to be packed before MultiPack
                 will switch to background operation
  -B Run MultiPack non-interactively
  -C configures MultiPack for user, but does not pack
  -S configures MultiPack for the sysop, but does not pack
  -P configures selected packer library instead of MultiPack
  -E extract messages, rather than pack them
  -O <pri> is the priority MultiPack will run at
  -F <file> is the filename to be extracted
     (required when extracting in background mode
  -L <library> is the name of a library to override
     the user's selected library

For the most part, you don't need many of the options. Simply running MultiPack with no options gets you packing. Add the "-E" message to extract a message packet instead of packing. If the number of messages to pack is less than the ram threshold, MultiP

 ack will use T:  for temporary storage, otherwise it will use the work path you specify (when configuring MultiPack). The background threshold works the same way. If it is exceeded, MultiPack will launch itself into the background and let the user do oth

e r things while it packs.

If you want to run MultiPack offline, you must specify the user name to pack for with the "-U" option (make sure the user's name is underscored -- ie: Mike_Oliphant). Also, give MultiPack the "-B" option so that it knows it shouldn't be prompting the user


 for anything.

You can override the user's selected packer library with the "-L" option.

Specifying "-C" or "-S" will make MultiPack configure either a user's options or general MultiPack options respectively. Adding "-P" will configure specific packer options instead of general MultiPack options.

Message archives are uploaded to the user's private file area. The ASCII packer library creates an archive called "ASCIIMSG.MO#", where the "#" gets bumped from 0 up to 9 depending on whether previous archives exists. The QWK and BlueWave packers archive 

 to "<ID>.MO#", where <ID> is the system ID selected by the sysop (in the packer configuration), and the number "#" is 0=9 as with the ASCII library.
@endnode

@node "prog" "Programming additional libraries"
 A programmer package is available for those who want to write their own packer libraries. The package gives autodocs for the shared library standard and other information necessary to write a packer library. This package can be file requested from my sys

 tem (1:377/31) as "MPPrg1_0.lha".
@endnode

@node "registration" "Registering MultiPack"
 The registered version of MultiPack costs $35 in US funds. Other currencies will not be accepted. If you live outside of the United States, please send a money order in US currency. Registering MultiPack entitles you to free updates for one full year aft

 er purchase.

MultiPack is available electronically only. I will not be mailing out registered versions. This makes sense for a number of reasons:

 o You've all got modems, or this program wouldn't be of any use
   to you.

 o It keeps the price to a minimum by avoiding having you pay for
   my time spent stuffing envelopes and running to the post office.

 o You get your keyfile faster.

 o The keyfile is tiny, so your connect time should be under a minute if
   you get your keyfile via fidonet.


When you send in your money, send in the following information as well:

 o Name:
 o DLG serial number:
 o Method of obtaining keyfile: (Fido/BBS)

If you want your keyfile sent via fido (I'll put it on hold), I need:

 o FidoNet Address:
 o Optional Session Password: 

and I'll put your keyfile on hold for you to pick up from my system.

If you want me to create an account for you on my system and put the keyfile in your private directory, send me:

 o User Name:
 o Password:

and you can log in and download the keyfile.


Send your money and the above information to:

Jay Ruyle 2728 Jetton Ave. Tampa, FL 33629 USA


*** Double check that you've given me all of the information I've *** asked for -- some people are forgetting to give me their DLG *** serial number.


If you send a money order, I will make your keyfile available ASAP. If you send a check, I will wait two weeks for the check to clear. Remember that it will take a while for your money to get to me, and that I might not check my mail every day, or I might


 be out of town every once in a while, so don't panic if your keyfile doesn't become available the day after you put your letter in the mail.

My Node number for fidonet keyfile pickup is 1:377/31.0 My BBS number for regular keyfile pickup is (813) 254-7493.
@endnode

